Subject: [sfraves] Real DJs code live (from WIRED)

LONDON -- Some DJs spin vinyl or twiddle fader knobs. Others write subroutines in C++.


  A new brand of music maestro is turning programming into performance, eschewing turntables for a compiler and a mind for syntax structure. "Livecoding" practitioners improvise using Perl or homemade programming architectures to build compositions from the ground up, replacing instruments and samples with raw code authoring before a live audience.

...

Evil Breaks, In Deep, and Sister SF are teaming up to bring you one of
the biggest Fourth of July celebrations this year. Located at Mighty
this event will be going till 4am with one of Breakbeats biggest names
as the Headliners. The Breakfastaz baby!!!!! All the way from the UK,
these guys are not only going to destroy the decks, they're going to
help us celebrate our countries freedom, from theirs....uhhh....well
regardless, it'll be a blast with 3 rooms of madness all night.




The Breakfastaz (Against the Grain/MOB/Passenger/SuperCharged) =96 UK
2005 Breakspoll Award =96 Best Breakthrough Act

Froe, Gav and Merf make up the nu-skool breaks collective known as The
Breakfastaz. They have been working together on a number of musical
projects for several years and the wide-ranging influences they
collectively bring have helped to form their unique breakbeat sound.
With over 20 successful releases and remixes on respected breaks
labels such as Passenger, Mob and Against The Grain in little over 2
years, their offerings have received support and heavy rotation from
scene stalwarts such as Plump DJs, The Freestylers, Tayo, Ali B, Meat
Katie, Aquasky, Krafty Kuts, Deekline and even catching the ear of
Zane Lowe, highlighting the enormous impact they've had on the scene
in such a short period of time.

Their hard work has already been recognised, with the guys being
featured on the front cover of IDJ's 'Players Of The Year 2004'
alongside the likes of Mylo and The Shapeshifters and also winning
Best Breakthrough Act at the Breakspoll World Breakbeat Awards 2005,
as well as being nominated for the Best DJ, Best Remix and Best
Compilation awards in 2006, too.

Subject: [sfraves] Re: Real DJs code live (from WIRED)

At 08:39 AM 7/3/2006, you wrote:
>   A new brand of music maestro is turning programming into performance, 
> eschewing turntables for a compiler and a mind for syntax structure. 
> "Livecoding" practitioners improvise using Perl or homemade programming 
> architectures to build compositions from the ground up, replacing 
> instruments and samples with raw code authoring before a live audience.

Blah blah blah....   Over 4-5 years old now in terms of the Toplap kids... 
this kind of started out of the supercollider community (Nick Collins et 
al) though Chuck / Ge Wang's effort is neat, but a bit more constrained to 
live coding than SC. From my perspective a lot of the early examples were 
so simple and trite.  I'm interested to see this develop, but toplap and 
the whole manifesto seemed like more posturing by a younger generation than 
actual content. I have yet to see a live coding concert that has moved 
me.  I'm not discounting all of it, I just think it is silly on a few 
angles.. That is all..

Best,
--Mike

Egregious
"Renewal through music for those outside the heard."
http://www.egregious.net/

  b=br0Qrjrt1W/Eout4kfU8v/jxBIAAf8YmlAy1HU901ogqG1BG8GRiBUKAXP1MhpdLwZm/LuCHecGacbqfXs/CYV6TEjxSQxuu7O7ZmS3Vta3P3ybmOZUEdL5ghNryTqi9F5UHsrJ44uy35bjE/EE2tle2xDY0BEZQ/Ze5LJHnvpM=  ;
Message-ID: <20060703202730.88980.qmail@web32402.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
Date: Mon, 3 Jul 2006 13:27:30 -0700 (PDT)
From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] review: sunset + stompy at cafe cocomo

When opportunity knocks etc.  At the last minute a babysitter appeared this Sunday afternoon and my wife and I managed to get out to the Sunset + Stompy event at Cafa Cocomo.

Pretty good vibe for a smallish Sunday party.  This event is a bit expensive for my taste ($10 b4 5PM and $20 after) but then beggars can't be choosers.  I had never been to Cafe Cocomo before, but its a good venue for this event.  The party starts outside on the patio and then moves inside for the final set.  That's a nice approach I think.

The usual heads were in the house and there were lots of familiar faces from Sunset and Stompy parties gone by.  Even though the Cafe Cocomo website specified "no jeans" that only applies to their salsa nights.  This was a "come however you want" event, though no costumes or playa wear in evidence.

I ran into my friend Doug that I used to spin with at the Monkey Club.  That was cool, and we're going to go record shopping in the next couple of weeks.  Made a little faux pax when he came by with some girl and I asked him if it was his girlfirend.  Whoops!  They had just met on the dance floor a few minutes earlier.  I'm not sure if he has a girlfriend actually, but this girl didn't seem to be too worried about it.  She was, umm, very friendly.

We met "Parisian Man" who was wearing a very interestingly colored camo Members Jacket.  I was curious where orange, purple, and tan camo was most effective.  Maybe in the fruits and vegetables section of the market?  He was kind enough to let us know that the French had "kicked the asses" of the Brazilians in World Cup soccer.  Too bad for the folks from the Brazilian Electronic Music Community that were at the party too!  We spent the rest of the party pretending we couldn't see him because of his camoflauge jacket.

Beams also to "Leather Cowboy Hat" who was dancing outside on the patio and commented on a story I was telling about my son Jack and my daughter Jessica learning to mix.  What a sweety!

Music was the usual SF house sound you'd expect from Pacific Sound and Stompy.  Whoever played last out on the patio played a really messed up B52s remix.  Now, I've heard enough B52s to last me a lifetime, but the vocals on this mix were really processed and it produced a really great effect.  We were digging it!

Except for the price, I'd recommend this event.  Good crowd.  Good music.  Good vibe.  Good venue for this event.

Peace,

Peter



---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Except for the price, I'd recommend this event.  Good crowd.  Good music.  Good vibe.  Good venue for this event.

Subject: [sfraves] To Everyone - Thank You for the Vibes

I don't like copying and pasting messages, but I figured that as long as it
took my slow ass to write this, I may as well use it a few times... 

With that said, I gotta point out that SFR peeps hold a special place for me
cause you guys have always been there when it counted for Terri and I - as
far back as 1998 when shortly after joining the conversations, our house in
Sac got burglurized and a week later we got a random check from SFRaves
people to help us replace some of the stolen items - people we had yet to
even meet face to face.  A bit has changed over the years, but it remains
that SFR is made up of people who really do make a difference...

; )

Dina


And now for the general update:

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
--------

I wanted to thank you all for the countless encouraging and heartfelt
messages - It's been one heck of a rough week and I appreciate the kindness.
I also want to apologize to those who expected to see me out this past
weekend.

Spending 5 days in the hospital was a bummer, but thanks to the docs, who
kept me unconscious for most the time, the week didn't seem as long to me as
it actually was.  The real tragedy was my having to miss out on a couple of
events I had so long been excited about.  I didn't get released from the
hospital until Friday evening, so I knew my night with the Smoke Breaks gang
in San Fran was a no-go and that sucked (btw, I've asked for a redo of the
night so here's to hoping I get another chance at a night with those crazy
guys).  

As for Saturday.  I initially felt pretty good considering my condition a
handful of days prior.  So whether it was a rush from the first night spent
in my own fluffy bed or  delusions stemming from the head trauma, I actually
was planning on making it up for Memories III... , I'd even worked out a
ride up with a friend (thanks for that, JJ).  Early in the afternoon Terri
and I went out to celebrate over a bite of ice cream (a new hospital-induced
craving) and with Channelz Records nearby I thought I'd grab a few new
tracks for the night, but after about 20 minutes of standing in the shop, I
was suddenly overcome by swooning dizziness and a cold-sweat hit me pretty
hard.  It was then that I got the first real worry that I may have been too
optimistic in my recovery timetable - and perhaps 24 hours wasn't going to
be enough time for me to get me back into performance shape.  But I'm a
stubborn ass and upon returning home, I flopped back into bed with hopes
that I'd wake up feeling like a new person.  Unfortunately that didn't
happen and at around 10pm or so, after admitting to myself that I indeed was
not well, I had to call Chipy and tell him I couldn't make it.   It hurt to
make that call but looking back on it, it was probably the best thing to do.
Friends have since told me that I did look pretty damn scary with my 2 black
eyes and I now realize how stupid it would have been to be out there away
from a major hospital if I took a sudden turn for the worse at the event.

So that was that. as for a more current update?

Well, I've been resting a lot. taking it easy and I've had more good days
than bad over the past few days.  I have another appt tomorrow - they want
to x-ray my dome again to double check I didn't fracture my eye socket - so
join me in hoping that that isn't the case. because that will really tick me
off.  If all goes well and the doc clears me with a clean slate in the
broken bone department, then I do plan on making it up to Tahoe this weekend
for Descent - barring any other unexpected incidents before then. I
certainly could use some time away with some good people!

Again, thanks for all the well wishes and while it's gonna take some time, I
have started sending replies to those who've tried to contact me during all
this.  You guys kick ass!


---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] Mutation:  Weekly at underground location

Starting up as a weekly undergound style event Friday Nights in San 
Francisco. Private location, after hours, DJ's, top shelf drinks, Absinthe, 
etc. Very discreet. Guest list by email RSVP only:

18andover.sfbay@gmail.com

Email direct to get on the RSVP list that will get you in the door. No 
RSVP, no entry. There will be a cover, though we havn't been told how much, 
probably $5-$10. Indoor smoking, no In's and Outs. Expect a lot of breaks 
and breakbeats. Majare will be there, and maybe Aaron Jae and Lucasz if we 
can drag them out as well.  Other DJ's, special walk ins and open deck 
nights can also be expected.

Some of you have heard about where it's at, since this will be at The 
Legion of Decency.  I know Danny's already got his card.  If you have a 
card, RSVP isn't needed.  People who regularly RSVP and show up will also 
be extended a memebership card as well.

Things will probablly get going around 11pm and go until late 
afterhours.   Limited amount of space and when it's full, the door will be 
closed.  All underground party rules are in effect.

DROW 4-Year Anniversary 7/15/06

Once again the DROW will emerge from the shadows of the underground.  On 
this occasion we venture into the daylight to celebrate 4 years of 
collective madness.  Your favorite dRow residents and special guests will 
appear in Golden Gate Park on Saturday, July 15th from noon until sundown.

DROW Residents:
4matt
Actual Rafiq
Bertzerker
synner
jason smith

And Special Guests:
ESKMO (Eskmo.com, Cyberset.ccc, Downbeat, Cyberfunk)
Dj Dice (straylightproductions.net, Straylight, JSA)
Kikipopo (Secret Breakedelica)

Bunny Meadow
Conservatory Drive West
Golden Gate Park (between John F. Kennedy Drive and Fulton Street - behind 
the Conservatory of Flowers)
( Yahoo! Maps, Google Maps)

WHEN: Saturday, July 8th 9pm - 4am
COST: $12 to $20 sliding scale donation
WHY: Help the Moonshine Saloon Art Car ride again - raising
funds to get us to the playa for Burning Man 2006!

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WANTED: Criminals, Loose Women, and Citizens of Ill Repute to
stock our Jail Cell
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Put on your Cowboy hats & spurs or Saloon girl duds for a night
in the Wild West.
Sexy Go-Go Dancers - See the Saloon  Girls (and Redstickman)
kick up their heels!

2 rooms of music!

The Dungeon:
Forest Green (SisterSF/Daly City Records/forestgreen.org)
Sinukus (FunkyCozy/Below Zero)
DJ Addison (Stargaze Family)
Jason Lee (Stargaze Family/SNDJ)
Powerlounger (Qool/Looq Records/Funk Camp/Fandango)

The Saloon:
Redstickman (Ambient Mafia/FnF)
MC Boomerang Fidget (Ambient Mafia/HATFYR)
Harken (Ambient Mafia/Epiphany)
drop (Ambient Mafia/butterzone)
Speakeasy Ray (Ambient Mafia/Hope Chest)

How to Get In:
1) Send a PayPal purchase (Services) to
moonshinesaloon@yahoo.com with your donation & your full legal
name (the one on your ID) and the names/number of people in
your party for the fundraiser ($12-$20 / per person)

Paypal deadline is midnight Friday July 7th!

2) You will receive confirmation and party location details a
day or two before the event

3) Your name will be added to the door list with  the number of
guests you've paid for

4) If you are unable to send payment by PayPal, please email
moonshinesaloon@yahoo.com to arrange another form of payment July, 29 2006 at FunkyCozy @ Anu w Matt Tolfrey 
43 sixth st, San Francisco, CA 94107
Cost: $5
  
     
 

 
For the last few years, everything has been falling into place for Matt Tolfrey. He quickly stepped up from playing at local bars to holding down residencies at Stealth and The Bomb, two of the countrys most respected underground clubs. Hes been billed alongside the likes of Richie Hawtin, Damian Lazarus, Craig Richards, Ricardo Villalobos and Andy Weatherall to name just a (very) few. Hes played at some of the best clubs in the UK, including regular slots at Fabric, and worldwide hes guested everywhere from Ibiza , to Berlin, to Australia. As well as all this, hes running two of his own labels named Leftroom and Leftroom Limited (www.leftroom.com), and he has tracks signed to labels with co-producer Craig Sylvester. Recently  Matt also has teamed up with Crosstown Rebels, by joining the new Rebel DJ Agency.

So how did he come so far so quickly? The answer is simple. Matt is a workaholic with a seemingly tireless dedication to forging his own unique style. Drawing on everything from deep house and techno, through to stripped down bleeps and Germanic mayhem, hes spawned his own hybrid strain of electronic funk. Anyone lucky enough to have already witnessed Matt in action will know that his particular brand of mutant-house has the power to win hearts and destroy minds on the dance floor.


 
 Below Zero Beats on 92.7 FM San Francisco 
Sundays 8pm - Midnight 
The perfect way to round off the weekend. 
 
http://belowzerobeats.com
http://myspace.com/belowzero
http://sinukus.com
http://myspace.com/sinukus

FunkyCozy - Every last Saturday of the Month @ Anu
 July 29th with guest Matt Tolfrey (Crosstownrebels, London)
 http://funkycozy.com

Really?  i could have sworn i did all the meth in oregon, that's why i moved
down here in 99.  Guess they made more...too bad i don't do that shit
anymore, otherwise i'd be in heaven.

I remember a few years ago when I was working at BofA, and one of the ladies
I was working with was asking about Oregon, and if it was a good place to
live and raise her daughter and all that.  So i started telling her about
it, and i was all like yeah it's beautiful and pretty damn clean up there,
and it's cheap.  But the only downsides are it rains all the time, and so
since there's not a whole lot to do outside when it rains, everyone stays
inside and to keep warm they huddle around the meth pipe.

It really is a good way to keep warm.

-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Fightin' cancer with one hand."
"Dead people are the new Potatos!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"

Saturday, July 15

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from Philadelphia in his SF debut:

SOMEONE ELSE - live!   ( foundsound . tuning spork . musik krause )


Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal (aka electro-kitsch-pop act Flowchart) brings his
quirky, dancefloor-friendly minimal techno to SF for a live performance as
Someone Else.  O'Neal is the co-founder of the Tuning Spork and Fuzzy Box
labels, and currently runs two more, Foundsound and Unfoundsound.  In
addition to his steady output of stellar original material and sought-after
remixes on some of the world's finest minimal labels, he still finds time to
regularly play live all over the world, work at the legendary 611 Records,
and hold down several Philly DJ residences. If you think you've heard it all
before, we think it's time you hear Someone Else.


plus resident DJs:

ALLAND BYALLO   ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D   ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )

________________________________________________

Rx Gallery
132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10
________________________________________________

Check our website for full bios, pics and lots FREE music!
http://www.kontrolsf.com

***New*** [KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

View the flyer here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14W.gif

View the poster here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14P.jpg
________________________________________________


BIO:

Someone Else is Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal, co-founder of the Tuning Spork
and Fuzzy Box record labels. O'Neal's production skills are garnering
respect among internationally renowned djs and labels alike, as reflected by
his releases and remixes on Musik Krause, Tuning Spork, Foundsound, Mo's
Ferry, Microcosm, Nummer, Tom Bone and many others. A stalwart of
Philadephia's deep house, minimal techno and experimental communities,
O'Neal also co-organized various events, hosting performances by Magda,
Matthew Dear, Sammy Dee, Geoff White, Jeff Milligan, Dan Bell, Dinky, and
many others. His current occupations focus on running Foundsound and
Unfoundsound Records, the former devoted to vinyl, and the latter an mp3
netlabel.  Since 1994, O'Neal has been the force behind his ever-evolving,
kitsch-driven electro-pop outfit, Flowchart--releasing dozens and dozens of
albums, singles, EPs and comp tracks on different labels from all over the
world.  He holds several DJ-residencies in Philly and continues to spin and
play live all around the world in places such as Russia, Spain, England,
Scotland, Switzerland, Germany (including Berlin's infamous Tresor Club),
Canada, and most major American cities.  When he's not making music, you can
find him working at the legendary 611 Records (Philly's most popular record
shop for dance vinyl) and continuing to write for magazines like XLR8R and
other Philly-based publications.


LINKS:

Someone Else's Website:
http://www.foundsoundrecords.com/

Someone Else's Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Someone+Else+(2)

http://www.foundsoundrecords.com/downloads/someone_else_-_live_at_the_bunker_nyc_-_07_may_2004.mp3

Someone Else - DJ set, July 2005 (mp3 - 69 MB)
http://www.foundsoundrecords.com/downloads/foundsound_-_sean_o_neal_aka_someone_else_radio_dj_set_2005_07_11.mp3

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Review - Elite Force

As of late my energies are being reserved for UK Breaks Producers/DJs, Space 
Cowboys & Opulent Temple gigs, Campouts, and kinky soirees ;)  So last night 
I headed out to see Elite Force at Anu.  I have always liked this place.. 
the bar tenders are hella nice (let me rack up $14 on my credit card to pay 
for door), and the drinks are solid!  The best thing was definitely the 
music.. oh and the fact that my date, so it seems, likes girls too 
(Yippie!).

The sound had some really loud spots since 4 mackies were pointed straight 
into the middle, but if you stood up front or in the middle great sound 
happened.  But what really turned my head was the amazing energy that was 
coming out of sHack's hands.. he was all over the boards the whole time, 
making crazy shit happen at every beat change.. waving his hands in the air 
at the crowds and dancin his ass off.. you could really tell that he liked 
his music as much as we did.  I love that in a DJ.. gotta respect the music!

Bad ass techno, funky breaks, electro it was all in there.  It doesn't 
surprise me that he collaborates with Meat Katie, those two are on fire 
these days.  I can't wait for the Finger Lickin / Mighty series to begin on 
the 29th.  Should be a straight up wicked monthly promising UK producer/DJs 
every month - WTF?? I think I just landed in something sticky lol.

Anyway.. we closed that place down.. and were about to head to an after 
party.. oh what?? I have to work?? ok so skip the AP.. let's just get nekid 
baby :)

~Ranger



SFR: Ranger
San Francisco
plurranger@hotmail.com
Who knows where the night leads
It's dark and no one can see

Hello Everyone,

Hope everyone is doing fine on a beeeeeutiful day :)

Most of you know that my car was broken into the end of july....
unfortunely they broke my window , my credit cards, money AND my big cd case :(
i had everyones cd's in there...i'm deeply sadden, music keeps me from going insane...

they took all of my favorite dj's (which is most of you on sfr) to my apoptygma berzerk tunes to my ORBITAL collection...*sighs* 

all my breaks gone
all my drum-n-bass gone
all my techno, trance gone 
all my ambient gone 
all my oldies gone..hey i'm a barrio girl..
all my latin freestyle gone 
all my alternative gone
 all my darkwave & synth pop gone
all my freakin disco gone...bee gees kicked ass
all of my rock-en-espanol...wtf gone..
so much gone...

i seriously shed tears when i discovered my case gone...


so any of you still have links up with your music on, please point me to your url..
or mail me your cd's or if you see me out give me a copy...i love music..it keeps my sanity intact...SAVE ME!!!!

love you sfr!!!!

~ adriana

I caught the matinee show in one of Century Theaters digital screenings.  I
thought it was good, but not as good as the first.  "Dead Man's Chest" had =
a
darker and more gory feel. Overall, the plot reminded me of the quality
found in "Back to the Future II", with the ending reminiscent of the First
Lord of the Rings film, eg surprise it the credits.  Looking forward to
PoC3  Aside from the plot, the look and sound of the movie was fantastic.

It's worth the price of admission - it's actually a
good movie, but I have to agree that Lois is the
weakest point of the whole thing.  The screenwriters
took a bit of license with the whole Lois & Supe
dynamic, and Kate B.'s portrayal of the character was
a little more bitchtastic than it needed to be...

but hey, it's Superman!  He flys around, bullets
bounce off him, he picks up cars, etc. etc. etc.  Good
stuff.

I thought the movie portrayed a great role model - Its ok to father a
child out of wedlock, and then have another man look after him who
thinks its his child - all because you have  bigger, more important
things to do, like 'save the world'

to stop by every so often whenever its convenient for him. I love it!

- Buzz

Subject: [sfraves] A Scanner Darkly



yeah, I ready "A Scanner Darkly" years ago.  It was one of those books
where I thought "There is no way in hell they will ever make a movie
out of this book, it is way too twisted".

Lots of Phillip K Dick's stories have been made into movies (Total Recall,
Blade Runner, ect)... but critics are saying Scanner is the most true to
PKD's vision a movie has ever acheived.

-troy

superman comes from danger that a good-ole plane and
missile couldn't stop.

------=_Part_78723_865271.1152564165703
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

here goes..

girlfriend and I had heard about a gathering on a beach south of the city
Saturday night that was to have "Goa" or psy-trance feel to the music.
Since I had not  been out to any outdoor events since arriving to the city
this was tacked on to the end of our plans for the night, not knowing if the
weather would hold out.  After parking, we made our way toward the ocean. It
was around 1am.  Many others we also arriving at this point so I felt "right
on time".  The moonlight was bright enough to walk by and soon the music's
baseline could be heard above the waves, so we headed in that direction.  I
found out that we arrived in the middle of Takuan's set and that Dr. Spook
would be coming on later.  Having had a a year filled with more mainstream
trance artists, Tiesto, Digweed, Paul Van Dyk,etc in a club atmosphere and
also one or two events like the Sf Precompression, I heard a  difference in
the style of music. It was more organic and flowy, fitting in with my
concept of the Goa sound.  There looked to be a single DJ setup with enough
sound to fill the area.  For those of you who have set up and played on the
beach I am impressed at the ammount of equipment that would be hauled to the
spot.  They had a single screen for visuals and not to far away from the
dance area was a bon-fire that in addition to making a "chill-space" made
its own addition to the visuals.  As my eyes adjusted it became a more
fantastic scene, the moonlight givng an overall illumination to the area,
blacklights highlighting as they do and the flames giving color and
additional movement to those dancing or chilling.

Aside from the fire eater and one person whirling some sort of spark
throwing mass, thre was neither poi nor hooping during the several hours
that we were there.  Dancing on the sand proved more tiring than I had
anticipated... and so we left a but before sunrise.  Overall I had a great
first experience.  While the music did not have the power and presence that
I felt when Infected Mushroom was here, I found it both calming and
re-energizing.

Can I tell you the technical aspectsof the system? Aside from seeing six
speakers decorated with blacklight reactive silks, no.  If they were using a
generator I couldn't hear it.   The crowd was about 100 or so people and
very relaxed and laid back.  I didn't take in too many other details, as I
tried to submerge myself in my first pseudo-underground, beach party,
trance, outdoor event.

dance area was a bon-fire that in addition to making a "chill-space" made
its own addition to the visuals. As my eyes adjusted it became a more
fantastic scene, the moonlight givng an overall illumination to the area,
blacklights highlighting as they do and the flames giving color and
additional movement to those dancing or chilling.

Aside from the fire eater and one person whirling some sort of spark
throwing mass, thre was neither poi nor hooping during the several hours
that we were there. Dancing on the sand proved more tiring than I had
anticipated... and so we left a but before sunrise. Overall I had a great
first experience. While the music did not have the power and presence that
I felt when Infected Mushroom was here, I found it both calming and
re-energizing.

Can I tell you the technical aspectsof the system? Aside from seeing six
speakers decorated with blacklight reactive silks, no. If they were using a
generator I couldn't hear it. The crowd was about 100 or so people and
very relaxed and laid back. I didn't take in too many other details, as I
tried to submerge myself in my first pseudo-underground, beach party,
trance, outdoor event.

----- Original Message ----
From: Matthew Phillips <kestrachern@gmail.com>
To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Monday, July 10, 2006 1:42:45 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Weekend reports?

here goes..

girlfriend and I had heard about a gathering on a beach south of the city
Saturday night that was to have "Goa" or psy-trance feel to the music.
Since I had not  been out to any outdoor events since arriving to the city
this was tacked on to the end of our plans for the night, not knowing if the
weather would hold out.  After parking, we made our way toward the ocean. It
was around 1am.  Many others we also arriving at this point so I felt "right
on time".  The moonlight was bright enough to walk by and soon the music's
baseline could be heard above the waves, so we headed in that direction.  I
found out that we arrived in the middle of Takuan's set and that Dr. Spook
would be coming on later.  Having had a a year filled with more mainstream
trance artists, Tiesto, Digweed, Paul Van Dyk,etc in a club atmosphere and
also one or two events like the Sf Precompression, I heard a  difference in
the style of music. It was more organic and flowy, fitting in with my
concept of the Goa sound.  There looked to be a single DJ setup with enough
sound to fill the area.  For those of you who have set up and played on the
beach I am impressed at the ammount of equipment that would be hauled to the
spot.  They had a single screen for visuals and not to far away from the
dance area was a bon-fire that in addition to making a "chill-space" made
its own addition to the visuals.  As my eyes adjusted it became a more
fantastic scene, the moonlight givng an overall illumination to the area,
blacklights highlighting as they do and the flames giving color and
additional movement to those dancing or chilling.

Aside from the fire eater and one person whirling some sort of spark
throwing mass, thre was neither poi nor hooping during the several hours
that we were there.  Dancing on the sand proved more tiring than I had
anticipated... and so we left a but before sunrise.  Overall I had a great
first experience.  While the music did not have the power and presence that
I felt when Infected Mushroom was here, I found it both calming and
re-energizing.

Can I tell you the technical aspectsof the system? Aside from seeing six
speakers decorated with blacklight reactive silks, no.  If they were using a
generator I couldn't hear it.   The crowd was about 100 or so people and
very relaxed and laid back.  I didn't take in too many other details, as I
tried to submerge myself in my first pseudo-underground, beach party,
trance, outdoor event.

> Aside from the fire eater and one person whirling some sort of spark
> throwing mass, thre was neither poi nor hooping during the several hours
> that we were there.  Dancing on the sand proved more tiring than I had
> anticipated... and so we left a but before sunrise.  Overall I had a great
> first experience.  While the music did not have the power and presence that
> I felt when Infected Mushroom was here, I found it both calming and
> re-energizing.
>
> Can I tell you the technical aspectsof the system? Aside from seeing six
> speakers decorated with blacklight reactive silks, no.  If they were using a
> generator I couldn't hear it.   The crowd was about 100 or so people and
> very relaxed and laid back.  I didn't take in too many other details, as I
> tried to submerge myself in my first pseudo-underground, beach party,
> trance, outdoor event.
>
>
> On 7/10/06, dangrsmind@yahoo.com <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:
> >
> > Wanna tell us some more about the party?
> >
> > I haven't heard the "Goa" label for a while...
> >
> > Peace,
> >
> > Peter

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Full Moon party at Ko Phangan, Thailand

The island gets very crowded near the full moon party and it may be hard 
finding decent inexpensive accomodations.  I stayed on Ko Samui (Mermaid 
hotel) and took one of the speedboat ferries over.  The hotel was great, a 
clean cabana on the beach for about $20/night.  And it was within a short 
walk from the ferry dock.  I'd highly recommend staying on Ko Samui instead 
of on Ko Phangan especially if you intend on staying for longer than the 
party.

The party is set up by a row of bars along the beach.  Each bar sets up 
their own sound.  So you can walk from one section of the beach to the next 
and hear hip hop, house, psy-trance, top 40 pop, etc.  There are something 
like 20 bars along the beach.  My preference is trance/psy-trance and there 
were two bars playing that.  I thought they had the best vibe but hip-hop 
was the most crowded.

Party favors were not easy to find and I gave up early.   Thailand has been 
increasingly harsh with their trafficking laws in recent years.  The 
government has been criticized for their shoot-to-kill policy against 
suspected traffickers.  On occasion, you will get piss-tested by the police 
at the end of an evening out at a posh club.  No joke.  Locals are often 
searched on the roads leading to the party.  And of course, there were 
rumors circulating of undercover cops.  So, your best bet is probably going 
to be to make friends with Europeans who are importing.

Subject: [sfraves] Late Grime City & Compression reviews :)

ok.. so a few weeks ago... there was Dillinja & Lemon D @ Compression.. so
we had a meet up w/ a few people... we met up.. well.. a birthday
celebration...

So we get to Compression... Mal & Ivry were on the decks tearing itup like
crazy w/ some hard dubby jungle :)  Yum!!  Colonel & Dino from LA were
MCin' that night :)  Yeah man.. there were Dope!!!  Anywaze... I went w/
all the other home for a bit 'cause some of them wanted to hang out
still.... but i just ended up goin' back to Compression by myself :)

OK.. it was Sick.. like i mean.. by the time i got back there, it was more
people, more family from all over the bay area (literally)... Dillinja &
Lemon D were Fuckin' Awesome!!  It was Dope.. like a few of us had this
like mondo kick step circle & we went buck wild :)  It was a Groovy
night!!  I'm so happy I made it out for that :)  I just remeber their set
like fuckin' being all hard bassy yummy jungle.. again.. i asume that they
spun alota their own tracks :)  But it was Fun!  Ooh my gosh man.. &
Fspund brought in their yummy speakers & stuff.. it was looooooud!!  Thank
God for earplugs!

OK... the week before that.. Joe Nice was here from Baltimore :)  lol..
the Ambassador of Dub Step :)  OK.. so i was suppose 2 go to a meeting b4
Any that night of Grime City.. but it was a no go.. oh well.. la la la..
but i did have an interesting conversation w/ a Leather Daddy for like 1/2
hour...

So i got to Anu.. hung out w/ Brice the bartender for a bit... slowly the
B I G crew like all got there.. Mega opened up.. OK.. YUM... he played 2
Step for like the 1st hour of his set :)  I was in HEAVEN!!!!!!

Then The One got on the decks... the two of them did this Grime tag set!!!
 YAAAY!!! :)

Then Joe got there.. he tore it up Hardcore!!!  I mean.. I danced as much
as possible during his set.. oh shit.. alooooota people showed up.. i
mean.. it was packed!!

Ohoh oh oh.. so i went like outside to smoke & this Homeless Dude like
pulls out a knife & starts like doin' that like Sagat stance from Street
Fighter wrestling stance w/ the knife in his hands.. ok.. then the bouncer
grabbed his stool & tried to like hit the homeless dude w/ it to make him
i dunno.. drop the knife... ok... so like i dunno.. the bouncer dude like
ran across the street with the stool & the homeless guy w/ the knife
started lookin' @ all of us & waving the knife.. so these 5 poeple from in
the bar rush out, 1 tackles the homeless dude, another one like kicked the
knife outta his hand, another dude rushed him to the curb, &* another dude
like knees him down between the curb & this parked car.. the police came
like shortly after & cuffed the homeless guy yada yada yada... by then,
the bouncer ran back to anu w/ his stool & started talkin' to the cops...
ok.. so like ok... i been hearing from the other employees @ Anu that the
bouncer dude is like this big hero for stopping the homeless guy la la la
& I'm like what the fuck ever man.. he ran across the fuckin' street..
LMAO.. Hello 2day!

But yeah.. Joe Nice Tore it up that night!!!  Fuck man... the energy was
sick & we wre all Happy Groovers :)  YAY

OK.. i think that's it.. i'm all cuahgt up now on my WR stuff :)  Hello
2day!!! *whew*

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Sat.July.15 [KONTROL] presents SOMEONE ELSE - live! (foundsound:philadelphia)

------=_Part_9411_14262458.1152736076291
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Saturday, July 15

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from Philadelphia in his SF debut:

SOMEONE ELSE - live!   ( foundsound . tuning spork . musik krause )


Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal (aka electro-kitsch-pop act Flowchart) brings his
quirky, dancefloor-friendly minimal techno to SF for a live performance as
Someone Else.  O'Neal is the co-founder of the Tuning Spork and Fuzzy Box
labels, and currently runs two more, Foundsound and Unfoundsound.  In
addition to his steady output of stellar original material and sought-after
remixes on some of the world's finest minimal labels, he still finds time to
regularly play live all over the world, work at the legendary 611 Records,
and hold down several Philly DJ residences. If you think you've heard it all
before, we think it's time you hear Someone Else.


*** plus special guest DJ just added! ***

ALEX RAJKOVIC ( mass transit : london )

Born and raised in Brussels on a diet of fine chocolates, Belgian newbeat &
fries with mayo gave Alex Rajkovic a taste for the finer things in life as
well as a militant approach to house & techno. Having subsequently moved to
Edinburgh, then Manchester & with further stints in Barcelona and London,
Alex plays city-music that, in the words of his euphoric-trance-loving
acquaintances, "never quite gets there". He calls it "hausno", they say
potato.  He is currently co-producer and resident DJ at MassTransit, his
London clubnight catering to this sound, as well as host of the weekly
MassTransitRadio sessions.


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO   ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D   ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )

________________________________________________

Rx Gallery
132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10
________________________________________________

Check our website for full bios, pics and lots FREE music!
http://www.kontrolsf.com

***New*** [KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

View the flyer here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14W.gif

View the poster here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14P.jpg
________________________________________________


BIO:

Someone Else is Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal, co-founder of the Tuning Spork
and Fuzzy Box record labels. O'Neal's production skills are garnering
respect among internationally renowned djs and labels alike, as reflected by
his releases and remixes on Musik Krause, Tuning Spork, Foundsound, Mo's
Ferry, Microcosm, Nummer, Tom Bone and many others. A stalwart of
Philadephia's deep house, minimal techno and experimental communities,
O'Neal also co-organized various events, hosting performances by Magda,
Matthew Dear, Sammy Dee, Geoff White, Jeff Milligan, Dan Bell, Dinky, and
many others. His current occupations focus on running Foundsound and
Unfoundsound Records, the former devoted to vinyl, and the latter an mp3
netlabel.  Since 1994, O'Neal has been the force behind his ever-evolving,
kitsch-driven electro-pop outfit, Flowchart--releasing dozens and dozens of
albums, singles, EPs and comp tracks on different labels from all over the
world.  He holds several DJ-residencies in Philly and continues to spin and
play live all around the world in places such as Russia, Spain, England,
Scotland, Switzerland, Germany (including Berlin's infamous Tresor Club),
Canada, and most major American cities.  When he's not making music, you can
find him working at the legendary 611 Records (Philly's most popular record
shop for dance vinyl) and continuing to write for magazines like XLR8R and
other Philly-based publications.

Client Support Specialist

In Ticketing is looking for a client support specialist to join our
team. Excellent project management and organizational skills a must.
Responsiblites include project management, providing on and off hour
support for clients and assisting with box office installations as
needed. The right person understands windows and can figure out most
computer related issues quickly. You must also have the technical
aptitude to learn our system and processes fast and support them. You
will work closely with the CTO to get projects completed and make
timelines for new projects. Job includes travelling to events
throughout the year.


Support Representative

In Ticketing is looking for a full-time support representative to join
our team. Responsiblities include answering phone calls from
customers, taking phone orders, online support and assisting with
printed ticket orders. This position is available immediately. Quick
learner with a professional and couteous phone presence a must.

of the Waldo Tunnel onto 101 south seeing the fog layer about 500 feet thick
just blanketing the bay was amazing this morning, albeit, doesn't provide
much for views when going across the golden gate bridge.  Looks like we're
gettin some warmer weather again-  woohoo!

When you have nothing but sun all year (born and raised in Arizona here) it
sucks. You pray for rain/moisture and if you are lucky, you might get one
5min cloud per week.

It really makes me appreciate the fog here. Dont get me wrong, I am glad I
dont have the 9 months of rain like Seattle does...but this constant
moisture is great. The change-up between the sunny and foggy just makes it
fun each day.

-Smith

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"

"Shine On You Crazy Diamond (I-V)"

Remember when you were young, you shone like the sun.
Shine on you crazy diamond.
Now there's a look in your eyes, like black holes in the sky.
Shine on you crazy diamond.
You were caught on the crossfire of childhood and stardom, 
blown on the steel breeze.
Come on you target for faraway laughter, 
come on you stranger, you legend, you martyr, and shine!
You reached for the secret too soon, you cried for the moon.
Shine on you crazy diamond.
Threatened by shadows at night, and exposed in the light.
Shine on you crazy diamond.
Well you wore out your welcome with random precision,
rode on the steel breeze.
Come on you raver, you seer of visions, 
come on you painter, you piper, you prisoner, and shine!



MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"  
--=====================_7868843==.ALT--

Saturday, July 15

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from Philadelphia in his SF debut:

SOMEONE ELSE - live!   ( foundsound . tuning spork . musik krause )


Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal (aka electro-kitsch-pop act Flowchart) brings his
quirky, dancefloor-friendly minimal techno to SF for a live performance as
Someone Else.  O'Neal is the co-founder of the Tuning Spork and Fuzzy Box
labels, and currently runs two more, Foundsound and Unfoundsound.  In
addition to his steady output of stellar original material and sought-after
remixes on some of the world's finest minimal labels, he still finds time to
regularly play live all over the world, work at the legendary 611 Records,
and hold down several Philly DJ residences. If you think you've heard it all
before, we think it's time you hear Someone Else.


*** plus special guest DJ just added! ***

ALEX RAJKOVIC ( mass transit : london )

Born and raised in Brussels on a diet of fine chocolates, Belgian newbeat &
fries with mayo gave Alex Rajkovic a taste for the finer things in life as
well as a militant approach to house & techno. Having subsequently moved to
Edinburgh, then Manchester & with further stints in Barcelona and London,
Alex plays city-music that, in the words of his euphoric-trance-loving
acquaintances, "never quite gets there". He calls it "hausno", they say
potato.  He is currently co-producer and resident DJ at MassTransit, his
London clubnight catering to this sound, as well as host of the weekly
MassTransitRadio sessions.


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO   ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D   ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )

________________________________________________

Rx Gallery
132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10
________________________________________________

Check our website for full bios, pics and lots FREE music!
http://www.kontrolsf.com

***New*** [KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

View the flyer here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14W.gif

View the poster here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K14P.jpg
________________________________________________


BIO:

Someone Else is Philadelphia's Sean O'Neal, co-founder of the Tuning Spork
and Fuzzy Box record labels. O'Neal's production skills are garnering
respect among internationally renowned djs and labels alike, as reflected by
his releases and remixes on Musik Krause, Tuning Spork, Foundsound, Mo's
Ferry, Microcosm, Nummer, Tom Bone and many others. A stalwart of
Philadephia's deep house, minimal techno and experimental communities,
O'Neal also co-organized various events, hosting performances by Magda,
Matthew Dear, Sammy Dee, Geoff White, Jeff Milligan, Dan Bell, Dinky, and
many others. His current occupations focus on running Foundsound and
Unfoundsound Records, the former devoted to vinyl, and the latter an mp3
netlabel.  Since 1994, O'Neal has been the force behind his ever-evolving,
kitsch-driven electro-pop outfit, Flowchart--releasing dozens and dozens of
albums, singles, EPs and comp tracks on different labels from all over the
world.  He holds several DJ-residencies in Philly and continues to spin and
play live all around the world in places such as Russia, Spain, England,
Scotland, Switzerland, Germany (including Berlin's infamous Tresor Club),
Canada, and most major American cities.  When he's not making music, you can
find him working at the legendary 611 Records (Philly's most popular record
shop for dance vinyl) and continuing to write for magazines like XLR8R and
other Philly-based publications.

Hi, I lost my job kind of suddenly and was wondering if any of you are 
working in places that might be hiring. I've been responding to a lot of Craigslist 
postings and listings at specific companies, but I know that the best jobs 
don't necessarily get posted. 

My specialty is editorial work: corporate publications, scientific articles, 
medical research, reviewing executive memos, creating summaries out of 
detailed reports, proofreading, and so forth. I'm also very strong in general office 
skills: 80 wpm, all the usual office software, can get printers unjammed, 
order office supplies, etc. I get along with everyone.

I live in Martinez and have been looking for something close to Bart, but I 
might be moving, so really I'm open to almost any location right now. 

If anybody out there has tips, names of contact people, anything at all, I'd 
really appreciate it! 
Thanks very much
John

Sometimes you just want to party with other fun professionals*, this is a

'The Professionals Party' *

100% benefit for the Opulent Temple.

communities only.

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Pacific Sound Boat Party, 23July

------=_Part_9608_9789145.1153154617204
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I've been on tons of Pacific/Sunset boat parties over the years and they are
always a blast. The cruises themselves last closer to about 4 hours, with a
bit of extra time on the dock as everyone's loading on.  As far as
seasickness, I'm not sure how sensitive you are, but I've hardly ever heard
of people actually getting sick from the boat rocking.  The one they use now
is way bigger than the old (Blue and Gold) boats and it doesn't rock too
wildly.  The SF Spirit (or whatever the boat is called) is actually pretty
huge (3 floors), so I never really felt "trapped on a boat", more like being
in a big floating nightclub with good house music and awesome views of the
bay.  If you've never been, you don't know what you're missing.  Highly
recommended.


------> Greg

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Barry Manilow - Australia's secret weapon

Australians Upset Over Loud Manilow Music
-
Monday, July 17, 2006

(07-17) 08:59 PDT Sydney, Australia (AP) --

It could be magic for some, but the use of loud Barry Manilow music to
drive away late-night revelers from a suburban Sydney park is getting
on the nerves of nearby residents.

In a move reminiscent of U.S. efforts to drive former Panama strongman
Manuel Noriega from the Vatican Embassy where he took refuge in 1989,
the local council in Rockdale, in Sydney's southern suburbs, started a
six-month trial of high-volume hits by Manilow and Doris Day to chase
away car enthusiasts who were gathering on weekend nights at Cook Park
Reserve.

"Barry's our secret weapon," Rockdale Deputy Mayor Bill Saravinovski
told The Daily Telegraph newspaper, four weeks after the start of the
effort. "It seems to be working."

But some people living near the park are less than enthralled. They
say the barrage of "Copacabana,""Could It Be Magic" and "Que Sera
Sera," blasting from 9 p.m. to midnight every Friday, Saturday and
Sunday is driving them crazy.

"I don't know how I will cope," said Moya Dunn, describing how the
songs have invaded her house. "I just can't sleep when it's on, and to
think there's going to be another six months of this."

Officials have given in a little, agreeing to turn down the volume a
bit after residents complained.

"The initial reaction was that they found it irritating," Saravinovski
said. "I'm not disputing what the residents are saying. I can't
swallow some of the tracks like `Mandy.'

"We have tried to reduce the sound and we are reviewing the songs. I
don't mind Barry Manilow, but I'm more of an ABBA and Celine Dion
fan."

In 1989, U.S. soldiers blasted hard rock music and news bulletins
about Panama at the Vatican Embassy in Panama City in attempt to drive
Gen. Noriega from refuge there. The Vatican complained, and U.S.
troops stopped the noise. Noriega later surrendered.
--

This movie did a number on me. As with the book, I read his little closing
statement and thought: "those could be my friends."

Good timing on the release, IMO, with the ramping surge in amphetamine
abuse.

This was the first book-to-film conversion I've been happy with in a while.
The whole animation over film technique really gave the movie that surreal,
mind-bending, disbelief-suspending air. Personalityless Keanu was perfect as
a burnt out addict.

My only complaint? Isn't the whole rehab corporation supposed to be
government-funded? Or weren't they gov rehab facilities or something? It's
been a while since I read the book, but that seemed like an important angle
to cover..

srg

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: A Scanner Darkly



I liked the movie quite a bit too, I highly recommend it.  I think Robert
Downey Jr. was really, really good.  That guy kept cracking me up.  Woody too.

One thing that I can't figure out... who did Arctor have sex with... was
it really a one-night-stand for drugs.. or was it Winonna's character?  When
he was a the scanning station, morphing back and forth between the two woman,
I was not sure what was going on there.

But yeah.. the very best part of the movie was the paranoid rants.  "Wait
a minute.. this bike only has NINE gears!!"

Good plot, good acting, and I thought the animation technique was very cool
eye candy.  Screw the summer blockbusters, check out Scanner for a movie
that will leave you thinking about it for days.

-troy

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: You know what is rad about 112 in the shade?

Well....

My studio is wired through to 100 AMP Digital Power
Conditioner/Surge/everything boxes.... and then all my
gear is plugged into Furman PL PLUS's, which I
basically use as power strips.

So, I have never worried about gear damage due to
power failure or spikes. Additionally, because I run A
dual power supply PCI-X farm, 2 Dual power supply scsi
bays, and 2 quad g5's, the shutdown sequence is too
complicated for most UPS systems out there....although
I agree that im an idiot for at least not trying.

What happened today was this:
My power went from 109 volts (which sux to start with)
down to 94 in an instant. I saw failure coming, and
began a sequenced shut down. All I can guess is that
while the files were writing to a mirrored/striped
array, total power failure.....  Somehow It broke the
mirror, although individually they are intact, and
fubared the file that was writing... the sad irony
being that I have a mirrored/striped replication of a
turd.

Luckily Im not totally retarded, as I have last nights
automated backup, so I really only lost the 4 hours of
editing and arranging that I did this morning.

Still sux.... but I think Ill take your advice and UPS
ASAP... At very least I need enough juice to run 4
800watt power supplies (Which would cover SCSI arrays
and G5's)..... 3000 watts... Any suggestion? or should
I just CDW for it?

E

PS... At least the crazy lighting is amazing tonight
:)

----- Original Message ----
From: Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com>
To: Sarilion <sarilion@sarilion.org>
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Monday, July 17, 2006 10:57:23 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: You know what is rad about 112 in the shade?

Well....

My studio is wired through to 100 AMP Digital Power
Conditioner/Surge/everything boxes.... and then all my
gear is plugged into Furman PL PLUS's, which I
basically use as power strips.

So, I have never worried about gear damage due to
power failure or spikes. Additionally, because I run A
dual power supply PCI-X farm, 2 Dual power supply scsi
bays, and 2 quad g5's, the shutdown sequence is too
complicated for most UPS systems out there....although
I agree that im an idiot for at least not trying.

What happened today was this:
My power went from 109 volts (which sux to start with)
down to 94 in an instant. I saw failure coming, and
began a sequenced shut down. All I can guess is that
while the files were writing to a mirrored/striped
array, total power failure.....  Somehow It broke the
mirror, although individually they are intact, and
fubared the file that was writing... the sad irony
being that I have a mirrored/striped replication of a
turd.

Luckily Im not totally retarded, as I have last nights
automated backup, so I really only lost the 4 hours of
editing and arranging that I did this morning.

Still sux.... but I think Ill take your advice and UPS
ASAP... At very least I need enough juice to run 4
800watt power supplies (Which would cover SCSI arrays
and G5's)..... 3000 watts... Any suggestion? or should
I just CDW for it?

E

PS... At least the crazy lighting is amazing tonight
:)

Yeah I'm around still. Been going to interviews and stuff. The start up I
was working for ran out of money and now owe me 6 weeks worth of work, and
it looks like I wont be getting paid any time soon.

Stressed out, I need to find a stable job,  tired of stressing out about
money.  Another thing taking up my time: Making some money buying and
selling synths on craigslist and ebay. Been playing a lot of GTA San
Andreas. Still putting the finishing touches on my ambient album, but don't
have funds to get it masted and pressed yet.

But I do need to go out dancing someday soon, I have serious electronic
music with drawl, and it has been a long time since I've been in any
altered/drunk states.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  A Benefit Concert for Environmental and Social Justice

--=====================_18905171==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit


SATURDAY, JULY 22ND AT 8 P.M. :

“From New Orleans to Bayview Hunters Point, a Benefit Concert for Environmental and Social Justice”

at the  Cellspace, 2050 Bryant Street, San Francisco 

The concert features multicultural performers Fely (from Cote d’Ivoire), Guerrilla Funk Recording Artist T - K.A.S.H. (Revolutionary Hip Hop), COPUS (music and spoken word), DJ Tony Moses, and special guest singer/songwriter Jonathan Richman.  Sakura Koné of New Orleans Common Ground and Bayview Hunters Point community leader Marie Harrison of Greenaction will speak. 

The event will raise awareness and funds for two grassroots groups working with low-income communities impacted by environmental and social injustice.  Greenaction for Health and Environmental Justice, based in San Francisco, is a leader in grassroots battles for a healthy environment in low-income communities impacted by pollution. In Bayview Hunters Point, Greenaction worked with residents to bring about the recent shut down of the dirty PG&E Hunters Point power plant.  Greenaction works with urban, rural, desert and Indigenous communities across the west, and help win victories against giant corporate polluters. 

Common Ground is a grassroots community-based organization formed by New Orleans residents hit hard by the Katrina hurricane and the abandonment of residents by the government. Common Ground is organizing residents and evacuees in the fight for social and environmental justice in the people of color neighborhoods devastated by Katrina and governmental racism. 

T-K.A.S.H is the Truth. Developing his skills on Bay Area revolutionary hip-hop group The Coup's Steal This Album, Steal This Double Album and Party Music, brought T-K.A.S.H to create his magnum opus, Turf War Syndrome.  The album features production work by industry-veteran and fellow revolutionary hip-hop artist Paris and chronicles tales of street life, redemption and consequences in the inner-cities of post-911 America.  In addition to delivering a message behind his music, T-K.A.S.H.'s works include social justice & community activism and non-commercial radio.  With a fierce focus on musical quality and content, and a guided intent behind his actions, T-K.A.S.H. inspires his audience to rise to the occasion and stand firm. 

Born in Cote d'Ivoire, Fely came into the world surrounded by a rich legacy of traditional Ivorian music. Fely's first two albums, "Amour Perdu" (Lost Love), and "Aude a L'amour" (Ode to Love), created a stir in the Ivory Coast, where they were recorded and promoted.  She filled venues such as Le Palais du Peuple in Guinea Konakri and the Hotel Ivoire in Abidjan, Ivory Coast.  A national star at twenty-one, Fely's success  in the Ivory Coast culminated at a special show "Dimanche Passion" sponsored by the national television station.  

Last November Fely released her first debut album in the U.S., "De Zere Gnan" (Meaning after war, an Homage to our Forefathers). She performed on San Francisco's public TV station, KQED, San Jose's public radio KKUP, and in a wide variety of venues around the Bay Area such as Ashkenaz, Café Cocomo and the African American Cultural Center in San Francisco.  

Copus combines the timeless quality of classical, jazz, world, blues and other musical genres coupled with original poetic verse and the result is Spoken Word / Millennium Music. Featuring the brilliant, passionate piano compositions of Wendy Loomis and the spoken word artistry of Royal Kent, the Copus sound bridges millennia.

 

Tickets for the July 22nd benefit concert are a $15-30 donation, sliding scale. 



 

 


MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Francis and Nathan Coles.  These two have been putting on what is probably

2 questions:

1 - Has anybody heard their Fabric mix yet?  I'm a pretty big fan of the
series in general, but it seems a bit hit or miss sometimes.  I saw Terry a=
t
the EndUp last year, not too wild or crazy really, but some nice steady dee=
p
tech-house.  Not too familiar with Coles, so I'm interested to see what kin=
d
of influence he brings to the mix. reviews anyone?

2 - Ben, do you have any idea of the timeslots for Terry and Nathan?  I
suspect I will be out at some other events on Friday (insane night btw!,
Swazak @ boca, dirtybird @ shine, dj funk @ rickshaw, etc) but if I have th=
e
latenight energy this UG sounds fun. my guess is that they'll play like
2-5ish? would that be somewhat correct?  I'd just hate to show up late and
find out they finish at 3am.

Thx, and see you fools out this weekend! ;)

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Full Melt

I know I'll be bartending for like the 1st 1/2 of this shindig... so enjoy
some of my yummy drinks & dance your ass off (well... not in that order
'cause u might get a tummy ache :)
---------------------------

FULL MELT
Saturday July 29th
10 PM - 6 AM
Undergound location
* 18 and Up
$15 before 11 / $20 after

Prepare for the return of the people who put the whoomp, whoomp, whoomp...
warble, warble into the San Francisco underground.

We are proud to present the cutting edge of the UK Dubstep / Grime scene -
DJ Distance and Pinch.
Both these people fuse post-breakbeat / post-2-step beats with extreme
low-end frequency manipulation.
Expect chest-caving, sinus tingling subfrequencies designed to move your
mind as well as your insides...
Prepare for comlplete meltdown !

DISTANCE (Hotflush, Planet Mu, Boka, Rinse FM)
PINCH (Tectonic, Planet Mu, Subloaded)
ATOMIKDOG (369 Rekchordz, Bassick Frequencies)
ZAPPER (369 Rekchordz, Ooze System, Bassick Frequencies)
DJ RIPPLE (BreaksFM.com, Subscience, Full Melt, Bassick Frequencies)
SUBTEK (B.I.G. Crew)
THE LEXXUS (Bassism, Turntablaze)
NICK ARGON & MATTY G (Argon Records)
CYAN (Soul Stream)
MAEBYN (Subscience)
* EMCEE CHILD (B.I.G. Crew)

ESKMO(Cyberset.cc, Eskmo.com)
MR. ROGERS (Ooze System, 840 Ent., Full Melt)
DOV (Muti Music, Cyberset.cc)
HYPNOTECH (Addictech.com)
BERTZERKER (Ataraxia, Full Melt)
BREAKBEAT BUDDAH (breakbeatbuddah.com)

2 rooms of EXTREME sound. Friendly security by B&B
Visuals & Lights by EYE & EYE
info line: (415) 820-1625
www.subscience.org


-- 
Take Care <3

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Question about Dj style table top Cd players and cheapest place to buy them

My advice is stick with Pioneer they are solid on the low end (cdj100) and
the best I've used on the high end (cdj1000), plus they're what you're going
to run into 9 time out of 10 when you play out.  Haven't played on some of
the newer models from other manufacturers but that's my general experience.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Question about Dj style table top Cd players and cheapest place to buy them

well, why do you need two?  and why do they have to be new?

unless you're going to be a mobile DJ where you lug your own gear
around, why not start with just one?

you can get a used Pioneer 800 for around $400.  that will be the
closest to "standard" that you'll find in a club, as far as CDJs with
scratching capability goes.

the most popular CDJs used in clubs are the Pioneer 100, 1000 and 800.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Question about Dj style table top Cd players and cheapest place to buy   them

Honestly, if you're like a lot of people these days, you might have a laptop.  If you do, I would skip the cdjs altogether and go for Final Scratch, or Serato Scratch, or the like.  There is still so much better gestural control with digital vinyl than cdjs, there's just no contest.

Of course, you may not have turntables!  lol

If not I'd go for some of the newer Denon offerings, preferably with the spinning platter, if you're looking for great functionality for your own use.  If you're concerned about becoming proficient on what most clubs these days use, then some variant of the big Pioneers is probably in order.  However, they are no fun to play on, IMHO.

Even the tiny little few-hundred-buck Denon feels more fun to me (the one that uses a CD as a platter).

-george aka optional
-myspace.com/newstylesound

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Question about Dj style table top Cd players and cheapest place to buy   them

i just bought a pair of CDJ-800s ($700 for the pair, barely used) and =20=

absolutely love them.  they don't play mp3s, but that's not such a =20
big deal to me.

I like the simplicity of a 2x CDJ setup over Serrato Scratch or Final =20=

Scratch. Easy to setup & transport (2 decks, 2 power cables, and 2 =20
RCAs), and I don't have to carry a $1500 laptop around.

BTW, George doesn't know what he's talking about.  It's WAY easier to =20=

spin and beat match on these CDJs than it is on vinyl decks, and it's =20=

FUN... especially with the master tempo & =B1100% pitch control.  =20
suddenly, all my records can sound like jungle!

I haven't used the Denon decks, but having used the Pioneers for =20
about a month now, I don't see the need for a spinning platter.

-Philip-




On Jul 21, 2006, at 8:49 AM, georgeC | origami wrote:

> Honestly, if you're like a lot of people these days, you might have =20=

> a laptop.  If you do, I would skip the cdjs altogether and go for =20
> Final Scratch, or Serato Scratch, or the like.  There is still so =20
> much better gestural control with digital vinyl than cdjs, there's =20
> just no contest.
>
> Of course, you may not have turntables!  lol
>
> If not I'd go for some of the newer Denon offerings, preferably =20
> with the spinning platter, if you're looking for great =20
> functionality for your own use.  If you're concerned about becoming =20=

> proficient on what most clubs these days use, then some variant of =20
> the big Pioneers is probably in order.  However, they are no fun to =20=

> play on, IMHO.
>
> Even the tiny little few-hundred-buck Denon feels more fun to me =20
> (the one that uses a CD as a platter).
>
> -george aka optional

Visuals were nice, tho.  I got some video and pictures - rel
schwanky loungey 60s style.  And security turned (mostly) a
blind eye to people smoking up.

I'm kind of torn.  It's great to see one of your favorite
artists get concert-venue recognition.  But it's also sad to
feel that you don't identify with most of the demographic they
seem to pander to these days.

All said, IMHO, loungey music should be played in a lounge, not
the concourse.

> laptop.  If you do, I would skip the cdjs altogether and go for Final
> Scratch, or Serato Scratch, or the like.  There is still so much better
> gestural control with digital vinyl than cdjs, there's just no contest.
>=20
> Of course, you may not have turntables!  lol
>=20

> spinning platter, if you're looking for great functionality for your own

> these days use, then some variant of the big Pioneers is probably in
> order.  However, they are no fun to play on, IMHO.

> that uses a CD as a platter).

Re: German Techno uber alles

They had so much soul in 94' that the sound hasn't changed much.

95% of the techno coming out make me want to scratch my eyes out, seems 
like a lot of people with machine drums and some virtual analog synths 
making their best imitation of stuff made on the real deal ten years ago.

Grats on being shit.

Meanwhile, I'll be at DJ Funk @ the Rickshaw tonight.  Cause he's shit, 
and I'm shit.  We're gonna be shit, shitty style.  And maybe I'll keep a 
candle in my heart that he'll pull off one of those 10% of the time 
miracle sets and take me away from all you bitches to a place where it's 
just me, and the beat, and lyrics about love, togetherness, and fucking in 
alleyways over basslines that make me space out and dance and alternate 
between a big grin and my "Oh"-face.  And I'll open my eyes and there will 
be no scenesters, just people who love music who know what's up.  Cause I 
never cared about much of the other stuff, drive thru.

<3,
andyw

p.s. the true Zen of being an arch techno crustie is coming full circle 
and hating on techno.  Ohm... chop beats, carry basslines.

Turning Point

Every single moment of the day you can choose a turning point. We are 
often too scared of making the wrong choices. However, the ! day you 
realize that every moment is a turning point; you will be able to 
adjust your choices at any given time. The energy of Turning Point will 
help you to understand that every moment in your life is a turning 
point.

Thanks to the Keys of the Arcturians and Janosh for this inspiration

SPECIAL NOTICE:

THE SFRaves Calendar is being fixed, tested and checked for various
stresspoints under test.

If you are interested in working on helping to fix the SFRaves Calendar or
know of someone who is interested in becoming involved with the next
generation of the SFRaves Calendar Project - please email
karina@hyperreal.org

If you would like an event posted to the Calendar, please submit to:
karina@hyperreal.org and it will be listed on the Weekly Calendar Mailing.

The SFRaves Calendar is located @
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2

Technologies: Zope: http://www.zope.org

Experience with / understanding / development experience with *a Plus* :

* authoring and building applications using the Zope application framework
(http://www.zope.org)
* ZPT * Python (http://www.python.org
* PHP
* MYSQL
* Plone

Please note if you are seeing issues with the current calendar (bugs,
errors, etc) please note that I am aware of them and am currently in the
process of addressing / fixing these issues.

Please send responses to karina@hyperreal.org

Alternative solutions are also being considered for the next generation of
this codebase. Other languages are being considered to enhance the SFR
Calendar Application. This includes languages specific to the development of
applications in a web environment.

-- Albert Camus -- *******************************************

Saturday, July 22, 2006 * 111 Minna, Amazing talented Dj with his live 
percussion all in one! *

Date & Time:  Saturday, July 22, 2006 more on this date 9:00 PM Location: 
111 Minna Downtown / Civic Center Hi everybody, DRC and akoma on July 22nd 
Join these two dynamic Djs for an amazing night at 111 Minna. The event 
starts around 9, but DRC and akoma go on starting around 11. These two are 
both successful Djs/artists in their own right. DRC has made S.F. home 
base for most of the last 10 years and is gaining more and more respect in 
the dance scene here in the bay. akoma is a Dj/artist that moved here from 
Seattle in November. His Djs sets are always mixed with him playing live 
percussion all at once. After only being here several months, akoma is 
quickly becoming someone that people want to work with more and more. He 
does music full time, also performing with two grammy award winning 
percussionists in a group called the Drum Cafe. to be on my guest list, 
just send me a message with your first and last name, see you tomorrow :-D

Saturday, July 22, 2006 *Redstickman,Ethan Miller, Fred Funk, Trav spin 
in drag! *

Date & Time:  Saturday, July 22, 2006 more on this date 10:00 PM 
Location:  Mighty 119 Utah Street @ 15th San Francisco, CA view map 
More Info:  sistersf.com/ Over the last decade, SISTER SF has provided 
a platform for female DJs to step behind the decks and be viewed as a 
DJ. no bias. SISTER is not anti-male. Sister is simply pro-female. Like 
many things that better with age, Sister SF has given San Francisco a 
party that year after year, somehow manages to top itself in both 
humor, entertainment, and music. For Nine years running, we've managed 
to morph some of the man-ly-ist local DJ boys around into fishnet 
wearing, skirt bearing blondes. We call this phenomonon: Dragnet - We 
Like Boys. So pull your skirt up and get over to Mighty. 8 solid 
Misters drag-teaming with all the resident Sisters. It's not 
testosterone that makes a DJ. It's not stilettos that break a DJ. What 
matters are the skills under the skirt. Past photos can be seen at: 
sistersf.com/gallery Sat. July 22nd Sister SF presents: Dragnet: WE 
LIKE BOYS IX www.sistersf.com/events.php It's Sister's 9th annual drag 
party! An SF classic returns with Sister resident DJs joined by local 
guy DJs--in drag. Thanks to everyone who voted to select our guest DJs. 
Nobody can rock a frock quite like... - Amber vs Ethan Miller (Friends 
& Family) - Audio Angel vs Smoove (Funketronic) - Forest Green vs 
Redstickman (BAAD News/Ambient Mafia) - DJ ICON (Sister NYC) vs Bam 
(Evil Breaks) - J-Fi vs Scott Carrelli (Satellite/Qool) - Melyss vs 
Fred Funk (Brass Tax) - Samira vs A:Dubl (Breakthru) - Seraphim Delush 
vs Trav (Seismic) Also featuring: The Improbable Orchestra - 
interactive sound www.improbableorchestra.com Get $7 LIMITED early 
presale tickets at www.mighty119.com Sat. July 22nd Dragnet: WE LIKE 
BOYS IX MIGHTY (119 Utah @15th, SF) 10PM-4AM . 21+ valid ID $7 LIMITED 
presales (tinyurl.com/enb9w) $10 at the door b4 11PM $15 after More 
info: www.sistersf.com www.mighty119.com

Saturday, July 29, 2006 * Naga Helix :: 7/29 in NoCal :: Grapes Of 
Wrath, Bodhi, Amanda, Parus, Catalyx, Wichdokta & more (California) *

Date & Time:  Saturday, July 29, 2006 more on this date 9:00 PM It's my 
great pleasure to present Naga Helix, an outdoor event in Northern 
California with 18 hours of psytrance from the renowned act Grapes Of 
Wrath and favorite local talent. Our Danish friends last visited the 
area three years ago and have only been to the country once since then 
so please take advantage of this rare chance to see them perform their 
incredible music live. The gathering will be in Belden, a resort town 
on the shores of the gorgeous Feather River Canyon alongside Highway 
70. Camping and parking space is limited so please share tents and 
rides. Also make sure you bring swim gear to cool off and relax on the 
beach! As the 30th is Naga Pachami (Festival of the Serpent) we are 
honoring these animals and all they embody. The snake's regenerative 
powers and waved motion symbolize the eternal spiraling of universal 
cosmic forces. Naga, the divine serpent, also represents the dormant 
Kundalini energy coiled at base of our spines which rises through and 
activates the chakras as we awaken to full potential. This entwined 
nature is also seen within the double helix of DNA, the fundamental 
path of life we travel towards higher levels of consciousness. July 29 
8pm - 2pm GRAPES OF WRATH - LIVE & DJ (Parvati - Denmark) BODHISATTVA 
13:20 - LIVE (Geomagnetic.tv - SD) AMANDA (Mistress of Evil - SF) PARUS 
(Auraquake - SF) CATALYX (Mindfull - LA) WICHDOKTA (Full Circle - SF) 
SPACETURTLE (Mindfull - LA) BELGIAN GOA MADNESS (Mindfull - LA) TAKUAN 
"The Pickled Radish" (TOUCH Samadhi - SF) Visuals by Taber 15,000 watt 
sound by Full Circle Admission is $25 presale on the website and at 
Ceiba Records then $35 at the event. San Francisco, CA 94117 See 
www.mindfullproductions.net for more info soon.

Wednesday, August 02, 2006 * BOOM FESTIVAL Magic *

Date & Time:  Wednesday, August 2, 2006 - Wednesday, August 9, 2006 4:00 AM
Heya, All! We would like to share with you information about a very special
global arts, music and culture-gathering that incarnates biannually in
Portugal. Boom Festival takes place in a stunning outdoor location on the
shore of the Lake Idanha-a-Nova, approximately 2 hours North-West from
Lisboa. Bringing together the latest in psychedelic sights & sounds,
phantastic art installations & workshops, this week-long event is a harmonic
convergence of people, energy, information, and philosophies, from planet
Earth & beyond. Synchronized multi-dimensionally with the full moon of
August, the next Boom-Festival is taking a bio-dynamic approach by
incorporating a variety of sustainable techniques, and Earth-based forms
throughout its infrastructure. Reflecting a harmonic balance of the organic
and the cyber-technologic, Boom 2006 maps the metaphysical framework in
accordance with Peace, Love, Unity and Respect. A very magical event indeed!
5000 BOOM Festival 2006 Early Bird Tickets are available now. They are only
70 Euro for 7 days. Getting there is no big deal. Reasonable flights to
Lisboa can be purchased on most of the European Budget Airlines, and
Transatlantic flights from America are also quite cheap. The Boom has
organized busses that take you directly from the international airport to
the sacred womb of the vacation party paradise. This year, Boom-festival has
extended its length to ONE WEEK! Great news about the timing of BOOM 2006 is
that it's not happening in conjunction with Burning Man, so the devoted
"Burners" have a chance to partake on European creative community
expression. BOOM is similar to Burning Man, but with a lake & great sounds!
Not to be missed ... For more info, please visit: www.boomfestival.org

-------------------------------------------------
Administrative Notes
-------------------------------------------------

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every week. To subscribe to the
list, send a message to: sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list:
sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

If you have events to add to the SFRaves calendar, please publish them by
Friday @ Noon to be included in the SFR Calendar Weekly Edition Mailing.

SFRaves is a not for profit entity serving the Bay Area & all forms of
electronic music for 14 years.
