A different spin




Where's the beat? At this year's World Electronic Music Festival, the headline artists will be bringing guitars, not turntables. It's a symptom of a genre-crossing youth culture, ALEXANDRA SHIMO reports, that has DJs wondering if the party's over

ALEXANDRA SHIMO 

There are some momentous concerts that signal a sea change. The July night in 1965 when Bob Dylan went electric is one example. Paul Simon's 1987 African concert, which introduced world music to the masses was another. And this weekend's World Electronic Music Festival, while not in the same league, is also one for the history books, at least for those in the electronic music scene.

CONTINUED:  http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20060722.WEMF22/TPStory/TPEntertainment/Music/


MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Vinyl warping in heat?

I live in arizona, and the easiest way to keep your records from
warping is to do the following:

Never, EVER EVER EVER leave them in your car, or in direct sunlight ever.

Make sure to crack the crate so airflow can still happen. The last
thing you want is to create a dutch oven for your vinyl.

In 110 degree heat, it takes about 20 minutes for a credit card to
liquify under the arizona sun in your car. You do the math.

My suggestion is to find some way to keep them cool. See if you can
figure out some way to waterproof them and keep them cool at the same
time. Ice packs maybe?

Acid Totem returns to Golden Gate Park with another installment of
BioRhythm.  This month we have an eclectic mix of music including:  House,
Techno, Breaks, Progressive and Drum n Bass.

Paucus (Beatdown Sundaze)
Ben Haus (Acid Totem / BioRhythm)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Thomas Kent (Ill Behavior / Modified)
idiot.box
Shinobi (Ground Zero)

Noon - Sunset
Free of course!

July's BioRhythm will be located at OLD Speedway Meadow- which is not at the
same location as Speedway Meadow in Golden Gate Park
www.acidtotem.net/biorhythm


Directions to OLD Speadway Meadow:
>From 19th Ave take Lincoln and head West
Turn Rt at 41st Ave which turns into Chain of Lakes Drive once you enter the
park
At the 1st stop sign in the park, continue straight and you will come to
another stop sign, continue straight and about 50 feet past this stop sign
there is a smaller parking lot on your right, and the entrance to the lush
green OLD Speedway Meadow. If the lot is full, there should be plenty of
parking if you continue straight on Chain of Lakes to the next intersection
at JFK Blvd.

-- 
Acid Totem Upcoming Events
======================

Free Day Party GG Park  7/30
Festival of the Sun 8/12 - 8/13

what I used to do for the scene. I'm hearing that there's an SFR party Aug

love to make a special appearance along with my trusty massage table and 
offer free massages to all, with any tips collected going straight to 
charity, of course. How about it?

Subject: [sfraves] Summer Music Conference SF

Summer Music Conference San Francisco
September 27th - October 1st, 2006
SMC Outdoor Festival =96 Saturday, September 30th
SMC All Access Passes are on sale now!

SUMMER MUSIC CONFERENCE the first annual electronic music conference &
technology expo in San Francisco! San Francisco offers a great
opportunity around the electronic music industry considering its prime
location north of Silicon Valley where so much of what is driving the
new music making technology, digital music, mobile, and online
distribution opportunities live. SMC mission is to bring together
professionals in music, media, and technology, to generate new
opportunities, create synergies and identify trends for the future.

The SMC Outdoor Festival featuring multiple stages is set for downtown
south of market San Francisco =96 enter on 2nd Street and Minna Street
from 12 Noon to 7PM on Saturday, September 30th. All are welcome at
the SMC Festival as it is a suggested donation only event. Additional
SMC events will be held all throughout the week at select locations.
Artists scheduled to perform include:

Ferry Corsten, Green Velvet, Miguel Migs, Doc Martin, Terry Francis,
Hipp-e, Nathan Coles, John Tejada, Justin Long, Julius Papp and more
artists to be confirmed!

SMC is happy to welcome panelists and speakers from INGrooves, AOL
Music, IODA, SnoCap, OM Records, Josh Gabriel (Gabriel & Dresden), URB
magazine, Vertigo Films, Nextaid, Electronic Frontier Foundation,
UbiSoft, etc with more being confirmed daily.

Keynote speaker Tess Taylor, founder and president of the Los Angeles
Music Network (LAMN) and the National Association of Record Industry
Professionals (NARIP) will kick off the SMC on Thursday, September
28th.

"I love the diversity and quality of ideas that often emerge from
gatherings like these about the digital delivery of music, one of the
finest inventions of mankind" says Ms. Taylor, a vigorous defender of
intellectual property rights. "Opportunity has never been greater in
the music industry, this is a fantastic time to be in the thick of it,
and I look forward to sharing my experience with attendees about
accessing opportunities at the highest level."

SMC All Access Passes are on sale now! The SMC All Access Pass
provides entry to:
=95 All conference panels & presentations
=95 Technology Expo
=95 Discounts to all SMC Events www.nitevibe.com/smc
=95 Backstage Pass for the SMC Festival on Saturday September 30th,
2006....FREE drinks from 1PM to 6PM.
=95 More opportunities for pass holders will continue to be added....stay t=
uned!
Check out the Nitevibe SMC Event Guide www.nitevibe.com/smc to see
where your favorite artists are performing. Events are being added
daily so check back for ticket sale info and updated performer
information.

SMC is excited to announce Temple and 1015 our two host venues
participating in SMC. Temple is the newest 20,000 square foot venue in
San Francisco featuring the only Martin sound system on the West
Coast, state of the art visuals and world class cuisine - opening in
early summer 2006. The newly remodeled 1015 is one of the premier
venues in San Francisco boasting 25,000 sq. feet of newly remolded
dance space and state of the art sound and lighting.

SMC would like to thank our sponsors: URB, NiteVibe, REMIX, M3 Summit,
Flavorpill, Earplug, Ibiza-Voice, Live365, 365Mag, Bigshot Magazine,
SF Weekly, Allen & Heath, Ruckus, VIP Trend, Friendster, Universal
Rhythm, SF Station=85

SMC All Access Passes are available here:
http://summermusicconference.net/index.php?option=3Dcom_virtuemart&page=3Ds=
hop.browse&category_id=3D1&Itemid=3D35.

Stay tuned to the Summer Music Conference website for updates and more
information on panels, artsist and exciting news -
www.summermusicconference.net.


For Sponsorship & Marketing, please contact: Jennifer Manger at
Jennifer@SFSMC.com
For Entertainment & Bookings, please contact Pete Fraser at Pete.SMC@gmail.=
com
For Exhibits & Panel Programming, please contact Dov Bruyns at Dov@SFSMC.co=
m
For Media Inquiries, please contact Betty Kang at Betty@PlexiPR.com

www.summermusicconference.net

Subject: [sfraves] Cabaret Law

Its real and awfull. Guiliani, the worst mayor ever on this planet used it
to shut down 200+ bars. We use to have undercover police in out events at
clubs looking specifically for illegal dancing. The bar owner gets a cabaret
violation ticket, about 3000$ then can loose his liquor license next time he
goes up in front of the Liquor Board, (yearly). They revoke his license,
he's out of buisness instantly. Then the landlord is happy as duck in a
barrel of corn, so he can now re-lease it for 10x more. Its all about money
and greed. 

This is one of the big reasons satamile rec. moved out of ny and to SF.
Whats important here is that you stop these Draconian racist laws from
appearing in SF. Keep a watch out for words like "Quality of Life" and
Guilliani proponents citing what a great job he did with the city. He
destroyed nightlife there, robbed the city of its color and spice, and has
forced thousands to leave.

Check out the Manhattan Institute in NY, its a right wing political think
tank that helped Guilianni develop his Fascist policies. You might think
these issues don't affect you , but they do, and its spreading with the wave
of Neanderthal conservatives in this country.

http://www.manhattan-institute.org/

Or check out Adolph himself.
http://www.solutionsamerica.com/
Don't believe the stats on this site.

Write some emails,

MIME-Version: 1.0

	boundary="----=_Part_17908_23943584.1154116756859"
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] Israeli Soldiers may have been in Lebanese territory when attack/captured

------=_Part_17908_23943584.1154116756859
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

You didn't really think the SFR list could go on too long without some kind
of political input did ya?

This article is taken from gnn and I've posted the link to the AP article
that was posted on Forbes.com.  I'm still waiting for more stuff to develop
on this, but I wouldn't doubt the allegations that israeli soldiers were
conducting patrols in lebanese territory, thus they were attacked and
captured in foreign territory- not israel as they claim- which would put a
whole new spin on this conflict.

AP article:
http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html



Article taken from  gnn.tv

Official justification for Israel's invasion on thin ice

As Lebanon continues to be pounded by Israeli bombs and munitions, the
justification for Israel's invasion is treading on very thin ice. It has
become general knowledge that it was Hezbollah guerillas that first
kidnapped two IDF soldiers inside Israel on July 12, prompting an immediate
and violent response from the Israeli government, which insists it is acting
in the interest of national defense. Israeli forces have gone on to kill
over 370 innocent Lebanese civilians (compared to 34 killed on Israel's
side) while displacing hundreds of thousands more. But numerous reports from
international and independent media, as well as the Associated Press, raise
questions about Israel's official version of the events that sparked the
conflict two weeks ago.

The original story, as most media tell it, goes something like this:
Hezbollah attacked an Israeli border patrol station, killing six and taking
two soldiers hostage. The incident happened on the Lebanese/Israel border in
Israeli territory. The alternate version, as explained by several news
outlets, tells a bit of a different tale: These sources contend that Israel
sent a commando force into southern Lebanon and was subsequently attacked by
Hezbollah near the village of Aitaa al-Chaab, well inside Lebanon's southern
territory. It was at this point that an Israel tank was struck by Hezbollah
fighters, which resulted in the capture of two Israeli soldiers and the
death of six.

As the AFP <http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers2.html>reported,
"According to the Lebanese police force, the two Israeli soldiers
were captured in Lebanese territory, in the area of Aitaa al-Chaab, near to
the border with Israel, where an Israeli unit had penetrated in middle of
morning." And the French news site
VoltaireNet.org<http://www.voltairenet.org/article142056.html>reiterated
the same account on June 18, "In a deliberated way, [Israel] sent
a commando in the Lebanese back-country to Aitaa al-Chaab. It was attacked
by Hezbollah, taking two prisoners."

The Associated Press<http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html>departed
from the official version as well. "The militant group Hezbollah
captured two Israeli soldiers during clashes Wednesday across the border in
southern Lebanon, prompting a swift reaction from Israel, which sent ground
forces into its neighbor to look for them," reported Joseph Panossian for AP
on July 12. "The forces were trying to keep the soldiers' captors from
moving them deeper into Lebanon, Israeli government officials said on
condition of anonymity."

And the *Hindustan
Times*<http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers.html>on
July 12 conveyed a similar account:

"The Lebanese Shi'ite Hezbollah movement announced on Wednesday that its
guerrillas have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon.
'Implementing our promise to free Arab prisoners in Israeli jails, our
strugglers have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon,' a
statement by Hezbollah said. 'The two soldiers have already been moved to a
safe place,' it added. The Lebanese police said that the two soldiers were
captured as they 'infiltrated' into the town of Aitaa al-Chaab inside the
Lebanese border."

Whether factual or not, these alternative accounts should at the very least
raise serious questions as to Israel's motives and rationale for bombarding
Lebanon.

MSNBC online first reported that Hezbollah had captured Israeli soldiers
"inside" Lebanon, only to change their story hours later after the Israeli
government gave an official statement to the contrary.

A report<http://arab-americans.blogspot.com/2006/07/update-from-lebanon.html>from
The National Council of Arab Americans, based in Lebanon, also raised
suspicion that Israel's official story did not hold water and noted that
Israel had yet to recover the tank that was demolished during the initial
attack in question.

"The Israelis so far have not been able to enter Aitaa al-Chaab to recover
the tank that was exploded by Hezbollah and the bodies of the soldiers that
were killed in the original operation (this is a main indication that the
operation did take place on Lebanese soil, not that in my opinion it would
ever be an illegitimate operation, but still the media has been saying that
it was inside 'Israel' thus an aggression first started by Hezbollah)."

Before independent observers could organize an investigation of the
incident, Israel had already mounted a grisly offensive against Lebanese
infrastructure and civilians, bombing Beirut's international airport, along
with numerous highways and communication portals. Israel didn't need the
truth of the matter to play out before it invaded Lebanon. As with the
United States' illegitimate invasion of Iraq, Israel just needed the proper
media cover to wage a war with no genuine moral impetus.

------=_Part_17908_23943584.1154116756859--

> >> http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html
> >>
> >>
> >>
> >> Article taken from  gnn.tv
> >>
> >> Official justification for Israel's invasion on thin ice
> >>
> >> As Lebanon continues to be pounded by Israeli bombs and munitions, the
> >> justification for Israel's invasion is treading on very thin ice. It has
> >> become general knowledge that it was Hezbollah guerillas that first
> >> kidnapped two IDF soldiers inside Israel on July 12, prompting an
> >> immediate
> >> and violent response from the Israeli government, which insists it is
> >> acting
> >> in the interest of national defense. Israeli forces have gone on to kill
> >> over 370 innocent Lebanese civilians (compared to 34 killed on Israel's
> >> side) while displacing hundreds of thousands more. But numerous
> >> reports from
> >> international and independent media, as well as the Associated Press,
> >> raise
> >> questions about Israel's official version of the events that sparked the
> >> conflict two weeks ago.
> >>
> >> The original story, as most media tell it, goes something like this:
> >> Hezbollah attacked an Israeli border patrol station, killing six and
> >> taking
> >> two soldiers hostage. The incident happened on the Lebanese/Israel
> >> border in
> >> Israeli territory. The alternate version, as explained by several news
> >> outlets, tells a bit of a different tale: These sources contend that
> >> Israel
> >> sent a commando force into southern Lebanon and was subsequently
> >> attacked by
> >> Hezbollah near the village of Aitaa al-Chaab, well inside Lebanon's
> >> southern
> >> territory. It was at this point that an Israel tank was struck by
> >> Hezbollah
> >> fighters, which resulted in the capture of two Israeli soldiers and the
> >> death of six.
> >>
> >> As the AFP
> >> <http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers2.html>reported,
> >> "According to the Lebanese police force, the two Israeli soldiers
> >> were captured in Lebanese territory, in the area of Aitaa al-Chaab,
> >> near to
> >> the border with Israel, where an Israeli unit had penetrated in
> >> middle of
> >> morning." And the French news site
> >> VoltaireNet.org<http://www.voltairenet.org/article142056.html>reiterated
> >> the same account on June 18, "In a deliberated way, [Israel] sent
> >> a commando in the Lebanese back-country to Aitaa al-Chaab. It was
> >> attacked
> >> by Hezbollah, taking two prisoners."
> >>
> >> The Associated
> >> Press<http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html>departed
> >>
> >> from the official version as well. "The militant group Hezbollah
> >> captured two Israeli soldiers during clashes Wednesday across the
> >> border in
> >> southern Lebanon, prompting a swift reaction from Israel, which sent
> >> ground
> >> forces into its neighbor to look for them," reported Joseph Panossian
> >> for AP
> >> on July 12. "The forces were trying to keep the soldiers' captors from
> >> moving them deeper into Lebanon, Israeli government officials said on
> >> condition of anonymity."
> >>
> >> And the *Hindustan
> >> Times*<http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers.html>on
> >> July 12 conveyed a similar account:
> >>
> >> "The Lebanese Shi'ite Hezbollah movement announced on Wednesday that its
> >> guerrillas have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon.
> >> 'Implementing our promise to free Arab prisoners in Israeli jails, our
> >> strugglers have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon,' a
> >> statement by Hezbollah said. 'The two soldiers have already been
> >> moved to a
> >> safe place,' it added. The Lebanese police said that the two soldiers
> >> were
> >> captured as they 'infiltrated' into the town of Aitaa al-Chaab inside
> >> the
> >> Lebanese border."
> >>
> >> Whether factual or not, these alternative accounts should at the very
> >> least
> >> raise serious questions as to Israel's motives and rationale for
> >> bombarding
> >> Lebanon.
> >>
> >> MSNBC online first reported that Hezbollah had captured Israeli soldiers
> >> "inside" Lebanon, only to change their story hours later after the
> >> Israeli
> >> government gave an official statement to the contrary.
> >>
> >> A
> >> report<http://arab-americans.blogspot.com/2006/07/update-from-lebanon.html>from
> >>
> >> The National Council of Arab Americans, based in Lebanon, also raised
> >> suspicion that Israel's official story did not hold water and noted that
> >> Israel had yet to recover the tank that was demolished during the
> >> initial
> >> attack in question.
> >>
> >> "The Israelis so far have not been able to enter Aitaa al-Chaab to
> >> recover
> >> the tank that was exploded by Hezbollah and the bodies of the
> >> soldiers that
> >> were killed in the original operation (this is a main indication that
> >> the
> >> operation did take place on Lebanese soil, not that in my opinion it
> >> would
> >> ever be an illegitimate operation, but still the media has been
> >> saying that
> >> it was inside 'Israel' thus an aggression first started by Hezbollah)."
> >>
> >> Before independent observers could organize an investigation of the
> >> incident, Israel had already mounted a grisly offensive against Lebanese
> >> infrastructure and civilians, bombing Beirut's international airport,
> >> along
> >> with numerous highways and communication portals. Israel didn't need the
> >> truth of the matter to play out before it invaded Lebanon. As with the
> >> United States' illegitimate invasion of Iraq, Israel just needed the
> >> proper
> >> media cover to wage a war with no genuine moral impetus.
> >>
> >>
> >

----- Original Message ----
From: Ben Haus <benhaus@gmail.com>
To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Friday, July 28, 2006 12:59:16 PM
Subject: [sfraves] Israeli Soldiers may have been in Lebanese territory when attack/captured

You didn't really think the SFR list could go on too long without some kind
of political input did ya?

This article is taken from gnn and I've posted the link to the AP article
that was posted on Forbes.com.  I'm still waiting for more stuff to develop
on this, but I wouldn't doubt the allegations that israeli soldiers were
conducting patrols in lebanese territory, thus they were attacked and
captured in foreign territory- not israel as they claim- which would put a
whole new spin on this conflict.

AP article:
http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html



Article taken from  gnn.tv

Official justification for Israel's invasion on thin ice

As Lebanon continues to be pounded by Israeli bombs and munitions, the
justification for Israel's invasion is treading on very thin ice. It has
become general knowledge that it was Hezbollah guerillas that first
kidnapped two IDF soldiers inside Israel on July 12, prompting an immediate
and violent response from the Israeli government, which insists it is acting
in the interest of national defense. Israeli forces have gone on to kill
over 370 innocent Lebanese civilians (compared to 34 killed on Israel's
side) while displacing hundreds of thousands more. But numerous reports from
international and independent media, as well as the Associated Press, raise
questions about Israel's official version of the events that sparked the
conflict two weeks ago.

The original story, as most media tell it, goes something like this:
Hezbollah attacked an Israeli border patrol station, killing six and taking
two soldiers hostage. The incident happened on the Lebanese/Israel border in
Israeli territory. The alternate version, as explained by several news
outlets, tells a bit of a different tale: These sources contend that Israel
sent a commando force into southern Lebanon and was subsequently attacked by
Hezbollah near the village of Aitaa al-Chaab, well inside Lebanon's southern
territory. It was at this point that an Israel tank was struck by Hezbollah
fighters, which resulted in the capture of two Israeli soldiers and the
death of six.

As the AFP <http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers2.html>reported,
"According to the Lebanese police force, the two Israeli soldiers
were captured in Lebanese territory, in the area of Aitaa al-Chaab, near to
the border with Israel, where an Israeli unit had penetrated in middle of
morning." And the French news site
VoltaireNet.org<http://www.voltairenet.org/article142056.html>reiterated
the same account on June 18, "In a deliberated way, [Israel] sent
a commando in the Lebanese back-country to Aitaa al-Chaab. It was attacked
by Hezbollah, taking two prisoners."

The Associated Press<http://www.forbes.com/technology/feeds/ap/2006/07/12/ap2873051.html>departed
from the official version as well. "The militant group Hezbollah
captured two Israeli soldiers during clashes Wednesday across the border in
southern Lebanon, prompting a swift reaction from Israel, which sent ground
forces into its neighbor to look for them," reported Joseph Panossian for AP
on July 12. "The forces were trying to keep the soldiers' captors from
moving them deeper into Lebanon, Israeli government officials said on
condition of anonymity."

And the *Hindustan
Times*<http://www.whatreallyhappened.com/hezbollah_soldiers.html>on
July 12 conveyed a similar account:

"The Lebanese Shi'ite Hezbollah movement announced on Wednesday that its
guerrillas have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon.
'Implementing our promise to free Arab prisoners in Israeli jails, our
strugglers have captured two Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon,' a
statement by Hezbollah said. 'The two soldiers have already been moved to a
safe place,' it added. The Lebanese police said that the two soldiers were
captured as they 'infiltrated' into the town of Aitaa al-Chaab inside the
Lebanese border."

Whether factual or not, these alternative accounts should at the very least
raise serious questions as to Israel's motives and rationale for bombarding
Lebanon.

MSNBC online first reported that Hezbollah had captured Israeli soldiers
"inside" Lebanon, only to change their story hours later after the Israeli
government gave an official statement to the contrary.

A report<http://arab-americans.blogspot.com/2006/07/update-from-lebanon.html>from
The National Council of Arab Americans, based in Lebanon, also raised
suspicion that Israel's official story did not hold water and noted that
Israel had yet to recover the tank that was demolished during the initial
attack in question.

"The Israelis so far have not been able to enter Aitaa al-Chaab to recover
the tank that was exploded by Hezbollah and the bodies of the soldiers that
were killed in the original operation (this is a main indication that the
operation did take place on Lebanese soil, not that in my opinion it would
ever be an illegitimate operation, but still the media has been saying that
it was inside 'Israel' thus an aggression first started by Hezbollah)."

Before independent observers could organize an investigation of the
incident, Israel had already mounted a grisly offensive against Lebanese
infrastructure and civilians, bombing Beirut's international airport, along
with numerous highways and communication portals. Israel didn't need the
truth of the matter to play out before it invaded Lebanon. As with the
United States' illegitimate invasion of Iraq, Israel just needed the proper
media cover to wage a war with no genuine moral impetus.

his back pack & ipod & ran down 6th.. so i stayed w/ him & his Homies for

Very Adventurous night :)

2 Grime City instead, but told people @ the club prior (I"m guessin' while

come by & pick me up.. la la la... never happened... so a bunch of us like
after partied @ Hive's place a few blocks away & man.. i was drunk by the
time i took bart back home @ 6AM....oooh... the conversations I had w/
sober people that morning on the train :P

Oh yeah.. the commute into the City that night was kinda fun too!  I
happen 2 bumpinto Maz @ Ashby & met some 5 yr old kid who talked alot!


http://s54.photobucket.com/albums/g100/MadWicked/Breakage%207-21-06/

Saturday was fun... lol.. after only slleeping for an hour & 1.5 then

heat of this year it seemed) for 5-6 hours, then getting dropped off here
again, then getting picked up to go City again (who does that?  go to the

So we ended up @ Mighty for SisterSF: Dragnet :)  OK.. so i wanted ot be

FWIW, I was in NYC from '87 - '97, and as a theater student from NYU, spent a lot of time near Times Square. It did change a great deal, and not necessarily for the better. It's the extremes that suck - the drug dealing and trash sucked, but the Disney Store sucked even more - THAT, my friends, is neighborhooed blight. Fucking Mickey Mouse.
   
  The thing I remember most fondly of TS is the art installations, like Jenny Holzers' signs, and most significantly, 'Look!'. Apot, do you remember 'Look!'?..
   
  Right in the middle of TS, there was a huge wall with three chairs attached to it, each chair suspended about 10-15 feet off the ground. You climbed up a ladder/stairs, and sat in the chair hanging off the ground. The wall was bright yellow, with the word 'Look!' in huge, black block letters. You sat in the chairs, and you looked out upon TS, hanging there above it all while the world sped by you. You looked. It was awesome. I can tell you one thing - nothing like that was ever seen in TS again after Guiliani came to town. And there never will be. 
   
  Nostaligia is best with your morning coffee....
   
  MK

he's out of buisness instantly. Then the landlord is happy as duck in a
barrel of corn, so he can now re-lease it for 10x more. Its all about money
and greed.

i post this every year just 'cause i know a teeny amount of sf people come
up to seattle for it. and happily it isn't the same weekend as love parade
this year. if you do decide to come up there's probably crash space on my
futon ;)

preliminary lineup:

FESTIVAL AUDIO Artists:
Speedy J : Green Velvet : Alex Smoke : Bola : Thomas Fehlmann : The Dead
Texan : Fax : Telefon Tel Aviv : Ryoichi Kurokawa : Apparat : Nortec
Collective : Taylor Deupree : Funckarma : Richard Chartier : Subtle :
Andreas Tilliander : Static : Jeremy Ellis : [a]pendics.shuffle : Murcof :
Mokira : Claude VonStroke : Panoptica : Kate Simko : Jacob London : Brett
Johnson : Latinsizer : Tim Xavier : Soultek : Plankton Man : Lusine :
Davide Squillace : Jerry Abstract : Son of Rose : Camea & Insideout : 1Luv
: Robin Judge : Nordic Soul : Kristina Childs : Jon McMillion : SciFiSoul
: Yann Novak : Plan B : Lets Go Outside : Randy Jones : Senor Frio : Ben
Milstein : SunTzu Sound : Logic Probe : Foscil + many more!!!

OPTICAL Multimedia performers:
Ryoichi Kurokawa (audio / video performance)
Speedy J & Scott Pagano (5.1 audio / video screening)
Randy Jones (audio / video performance)

DB-CONFERENCE participants:
Ableton Live : Live 6
Livid : Union VJ
M-Audio : Pro-Tools
Native Instruments : Kore
Rane : TTM 57SL
Reason : Mastering, hosted by Andreas Tilliander
Robotspeak Sessions with Lusine
Panel Topic: Music Discovery and Distribution in the Digital Age

-> PARTNERS

Easy Street Records : Igloo Magazine : KBCS 91.3 FM : KEXP 90.3 FM :
Kohort Distribution : Mayors Office of Film and Music : Nonsequitur :
Neuton Distribution : Plexipixel : RANE : Remix Magazine : Robotspeak :
www.Samurai.fm : Sonic Bids : The Stranger : XLR8R : PlayNetwork

-> ABOUT

Founded in 2003, Decibel Festival bridges the gap between technology and
creativity through visual art, workshops, panel discussions and
cutting-edge electronic music performances. By gathering a diverse
selection of international talent, Decibel Festival provides a forum for
musicians, industry professionals and educators alike.

Details will continue to be added to http://www.decibelfestival.com/2006
as they are confirmed.

Subject: [sfraves] stolen records

hey guys,

friday night, word of mouth held a party in the
bayview area.  i'm tossing this request out to anyone
who might have attended, who might have seen something
- anything.  i was hoping after a couple days that i'd
hear word from someone that my bag was in a crew
member's car from strike and they just didn't see it,
but that hasn't happened.  

my record bag is a black technics soft case with a
pair of silver sony's in the front pocket, and about
40 tech-house and breaks records with a few downtempo
in the front.  this soft case doesn't have any padding
- it looks more like a shoulder bag, and
on the front is technics written in white script. 
it's also a little ripped up and abused but there are
no distinguishable stickers or writing on it.  this is
a small list of records that i can remember having in
there:

Alex Under - "Sorbere Cerebros EP"  [Trapez]
Ben-G - "Barnadango"  [Funkdango]
Jamie Anderson - "Counter Strike"  [Fixia]
Jake Childs & LBO - "Invisible Inc EP"  [Uniform
Black]
Chus Duran - "So Fresh"  [Funkdango]
Claude Young - "Electronic Dissident"  [Dust Science]
Bobby Peru - "Blood Money"  [2020 Vision]
Prefuse 73 - "92 Vs. 02 Collection" [Warp Records]
Tosca - "Dehli9" [K7]

it was in my back seat (i have a dark blue jetta with
a 'i hate your suv' sticker on the back). we arrived
at the loc. around 9:30pm to offload, and i'll be
honest - i didn't unload it from my car. i grabbed
larger items from the back, dropped them off, and when
i came back it wasn't there anymore - it was assumedly
brought to the location by a crew member and i left it
at that.  strike came around and it still wasn't
anywhere. 

any information - anything at all - that you may have
about my bag would be greatly appreciated.  if you saw
it, where you saw it and WHEN you saw it would be
incredibly helpful.  

you can reach me anytime via this email addy - 

thanks,
shelley

----- Original Message ----
From: Calamity Jane <scarpetta80@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Monday, July 31, 2006 11:43:14 AM
Subject: [sfraves] stolen records

hey guys,

friday night, word of mouth held a party in the
bayview area.  i'm tossing this request out to anyone
who might have attended, who might have seen something
- anything.  i was hoping after a couple days that i'd
hear word from someone that my bag was in a crew
member's car from strike and they just didn't see it,
but that hasn't happened.  

my record bag is a black technics soft case with a
pair of silver sony's in the front pocket, and about
40 tech-house and breaks records with a few downtempo
in the front.  this soft case doesn't have any padding
- it looks more like a shoulder bag, and
on the front is technics written in white script. 
it's also a little ripped up and abused but there are
no distinguishable stickers or writing on it.  this is
a small list of records that i can remember having in
there:

Alex Under - "Sorbere Cerebros EP"  [Trapez]
Ben-G - "Barnadango"  [Funkdango]
Jamie Anderson - "Counter Strike"  [Fixia]
Jake Childs & LBO - "Invisible Inc EP"  [Uniform
Black]
Chus Duran - "So Fresh"  [Funkdango]
Claude Young - "Electronic Dissident"  [Dust Science]
Bobby Peru - "Blood Money"  [2020 Vision]
Prefuse 73 - "92 Vs. 02 Collection" [Warp Records]
Tosca - "Dehli9" [K7]

it was in my back seat (i have a dark blue jetta with
a 'i hate your suv' sticker on the back). we arrived
at the loc. around 9:30pm to offload, and i'll be
honest - i didn't unload it from my car. i grabbed
larger items from the back, dropped them off, and when
i came back it wasn't there anymore - it was assumedly
brought to the location by a crew member and i left it
at that.  strike came around and it still wasn't
anywhere. 

any information - anything at all - that you may have
about my bag would be greatly appreciated.  if you saw
it, where you saw it and WHEN you saw it would be
incredibly helpful.  

you can reach me anytime via this email addy - 

thanks,
shelley
